<br>
It's a tough situation for an enchanter cause they see a mob and a player facing off.  So one of 2 things is happening:<br>
1. Someone is taunting the mob for you<br>
2. Someone screwed up assist (far more likely in my experience)<br>
<br>
If #2 is true, casting a mez on that mob will most likely be suicide since it will instantly be woken up and decide to have enchanter for lunch.  So you can either try to mez or yell at the tank.  Tough call, but usually I won't be screaming unless I see:<br>
<br>
big_angry_mob has been mesmerized.<br>
Your Dazzle spell has worn off.<br>
<br>
Maybe let the chanter know at the start of the raid that you will be using non-damaging spells to taunt mobs off them.  Could save a lot of anxiety.<br>
<br>
PS. Ranger root breaks mez <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> </font><P><P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#D5D4D5><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ufelisandria.showPublicProfile?language=EN>felisandria</A></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>p0\/\/3r-p0sT3r!</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#000033>5/11/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#000033>11:26:11 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: It's not that hard - part I (Assisting)</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Actually Vache, my comment wasn't at all directed toward the chanters.  Every chanter I've ever played with has known that my snare isn't going to break mez on the mob.  I've gotten yelled at mostly by melees (who later turned out to be the culprit, actually... they thought that the fact that the mob went after me made me the culprit (snares have VERY high aggro), when in fact they were hitting assist during the taunt round without knowing it would instantly attack.  Though how you can miss that boggles the mind.)<br>
<br>
Now, if I'm going to be doing special case stuff I let the chanter know (my root does damage so it breaks the mez.  When mobs are low MR and we don't have many chanters, my husband often has me break the mez by rooting the mob after he's taunted it twice, as an extra backup step to keeping them from eating the chanter.  We're sitting in the same room so we can react to each other instantaneously, which makes it easy.)  I really wish druids got a non-damage root, would make things so much easier.  If you're going to be using your damage root to help the chanter, you'd better have spell notifications turned on and duck out if the chanter starts to cast, whether you think they're on the mob you're on or not.  My usual tactic, in dire situations when the chanter needs help, is to snare one mob, pull it back away from the group and the chanter with that aggro, and then hit the root button, but if I see a cast message on the chanter I will duck out and try again if the mob I'm on didn't get mezzed.<br>
<br>
Hint to druids... during big pulls like Fear break, it's often a good idea to know who all your enchanters are, and /target cycle through their names healing the ones who are going down hard.  Your nuke isn't going to make that big of a difference, but that little bit more healing that keeps the chanter alive when the chanter's healer just can't mash the button fast enough will make a huge difference, sometimes a big enough to be the difference between whether or not your raiding party survives.  Also know who your clerics are, and if you see a &quot;casting interrupted&quot; message from them, it's often a good idea to /target and see if they need help.<br>
<br>
